<div class="tw-foot p">
<div class="fn" id="TFN1">
<sup>a</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P39">Column percent of the total.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN2">
<sup>b</sup><p class="display-inline" id="P40">Row percent of the total.</p>
</div>
<div class="fn" id="TFN3"><p id="P41">NP/PA, nurse practitioner and physician assistant, HCPs, healthcare providers, ED, emergency department; ENT, ear, nose, and throat.</p></div>
</div></section><p id="P16">Compared with GPs, ED-HCPs were more likely to prescribe opioids to patients with acute pain conditions with an orthopedic (OR=1.31, 95% CI=1.29, 1.32) dental (OR=1.50, 95% CI=1.48, 1.53) or ENT (OR=1.93, 95% CI=1.85, 2.0) origin when controlling for patient characteristics such as age, gender, and race/ethnicity (<a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>). Similarly, NP/PAs were more likely to prescribe opioids for acute pain conditions like orthopedic (OR=1.02, 95% CI=1.0, 1.04), dental (OR=1.05, 95% CI=1.02, 1.08), or ENT (otalgia) (OR=1.08, 95% CI=1.02, 1.16) than were GPs, and less likely to prescribe opioids for chronic pain conditions like headache (OR=0.88, 95% CI=0.86, 0.91), back pain (OR=0.89, 95% CI=0.87, 0.92), or neck pain (OR=0.94, 95% CI=0.91, 0.98). Other HCPs were less likely to prescribe an opioid for dental, orthopedic, and headache pain and were more likely to provide an opioid for back or neck pain compared with GPs.</p>
